In general if I have that
\begin{equation}
\mathbb{E}(X)<\infty
\end{equation}
does this imply that $|X|<\infty$ a.s? An attempted proof: Let $(\Omega,\mathbb{F},\mathbb{P})$ be a probability space and $K>0$ be a constant, then
\begin{equation}
\mathbb{E}(X)=\int_{\Omega}XdP\,=\int_{\{|X|\leq K \}}XdP\,+\int_{\{|X|>K\}}XdP\, <\infty
\end{equation}
Taking the limit as $K\rightarrow \infty$
\begin{equation}
\int_{\{|X|>K\}}XdP\, \rightarrow 0
\end{equation}
Struggling how to finish from here or posssibly this isn't true?  Thanks!

